
[1]subjunctive

   SUBJUNCTIVE, a. [L. See Subjoin.]

   1. Subjoined or added to something before said or written.

   2. In grammar, designating a form of verbs which follow other verbs or
   words expressing condition, hypothesis or contingency; as, veni ut me
   videas, I came that you may see me; Si fecerint aequum, if they should
   do what is just.

   3. Subjunctive is often used as a noun, denoting the subjunctive mode.
